SIMPLE: oriel
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Oriel
<hw>O"ri*el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>oriol</ets>
gallery, corridor, LL. <ets>oriolum</ets> portico, hall, prob. fr. L.
<ets>aureolus</ets> gilded, applied to an apartment decorated with
gilding. See <er>Oriole</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Formerly written also
<asp>oriol</asp>, <asp>oryal</asp>, <asp>oryall</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A gallery for minstrels.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>W. Hamper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small apartment next a hall, where certain persons
were accustomed to dine; a sort of recess.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Cowell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A bay window. See <er>Bay
window</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The beams that thro' the <qex>oriel</qex> shine⟦br⟧
Make prisms in every carven glass.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ There is no generally admitted difference between a bay
window and an oriel. In the United States the latter name is often
applied to bay windows which are small, and either polygonal or round;
also, to such as are corbeled out from the wall instead of resting on
the ground.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oriency</ent>⟦br⟧
